    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "it seems like the nutrients are just disappearing though. like i add stuff but the leaves still look starved. is there something that could be actually stealing the nutrients away from the roots before the plant can even get them?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "It's possible that pests or diseases are sucking the nutrients out of your soil before the roots can absorb them. Pests like aphids, spider mites, or whiteflies can feed on plant sap, leaving it weak and stunted. Fungal diseases like root rot or fungal leaf spots can also break down plant tissues, releasing nutrients that plants have invested in growth.\n\nOther possibilities include soil-borne pathogens like fusarium or pythium, which can infect roots and steal nutrients. Even gnats and other tiny insects can be nuisances, sucking out nutrients from the soil through their feeding activities. You may need to repot the affected plants, inspect the soil and roots for pests and diseases, and apply targeted treatments to get their nutrient supply back on track.",
